print('a' in S) #Output is True
print('x' in S) #Output is FalseEnter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen modeThe number of unique elements in a set is called Cardinality.The cardinality of S is 8.|S| = 8#python code
print(len(S)) #Output is 8Enter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen modeSet equivalence is when two or more sets have the same cardinality.S is equivalent to V.#python code
def areSetsEquivalent(setA, setB):
    if len(setA) == len(setB):
        return True
    else:
        return False

print(areSetsEquivalent(S, V)) # Output is trueEnter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen modeOperationsCartisian ProductIn Set Theory, there is an operation called Cartisian product.It is denoted as:S x V;And read as:S cross V.It is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is in A and b is in B.A x B = { (a,b) | a ∈ A and b ∈ B}{a1, a2} x {b1, b2} =  { (a1, b1), (a1, b2), (a2, b1), (a2, b2) }ExampleA = {1 , 2}B = {3, 4}A x B = { (1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4) }The cardinality of the Cartesian product is equal to the product of the Cardinality of the sets.|A x B| = |A| * |B|;|A x B| = 2 * 2;|A x B| = 4;#python code
from itertools import product
A = {1 , 2}
B = {3, 4}
print(set(product(A, B))) #Output {(2, 3), (2, 4), (1, 3), (1, 4)}Enter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen modeUnionThe union of a collection of sets is a set that contains all the elements of those sets.A ∪ B = {x | x ∈ A or x ∈ B}Example:A = {1 , 2}B = {3, 4}A ∪ B = {1, 2, 3, 4}#python code
A = {1 , 2}
B = {3, 4}

print(A.union(B)) # Output {1, 2, 3, 4}Enter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen modeIntersectionThe intersection of sets are all those objects that are common on all the sets.A ∩ B = {x | x ∈ A and x ∈ B}Example:Y = {1, 2, 3}Z = {3, 4, 5}Y ∩ Z = {3}#python code
Y = {1, 2, 3}
Z = {3, 4, 5}

print(Y.intersection(Z)) #Output {3}Enter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen modeConclusionAs you can see, python provide a lot of tools to work with sets. The topics exposed on the content above are just an introduction to the Set theory. There is a lot more related the topic, such as, Difference and complement, Disjoint sets, Naturally Disjoint sets, partition of sets, subsets and power sets. I would discuss all of those topics in different posts.Written by: E. A. Arroyo.
